 The sane people he is referring to are the ones who take this view.
The pattern we are talking about is above all this, so let those who know only the senses and their faculties turn a deaf ear to it, and refer to his team of those who know the outward appearance of the worldly life, but are oblivious to the hereafter.
If you are one of those who are satisfied with this kind of hint and reference to what is in the divine world and do not load our words with the meanings that they are accustomed to loading them with, we will add to you something of what Hayy ibn Yaqzaan witnessed in the place of the first of the truthful, which was mentioned above. After pure absorption, complete annihilation, and the truth of arrival, he saw the supreme ark, which has no body, and he saw a self that is innocent of matter, which is not the self of the One True, nor is it the self of the ark, nor is it anything else, like the image of the sun that appears in a mirror, which is neither the sun nor the mirror, nor is it anything else.
He saw the self of that ark in all its perfection, splendor, and beauty, which is too great to be described with a tongue and too subtle to be clothed with a letter or sound, and he saw it in the utmost pleasure, delight, and joy at the sight of the true Self, Glory be to Him.
He also saw for the next astronomy - the astronomy of the fixed planets - a self that is also innocent of matter, neither the self of the True One, nor the self of the higher astronomy, nor itself, nor anything else, as if the image of the sun that appears in a mirror had been reflected to it from another mirror opposite the sun.
He saw this self also as pompous, beautiful, and pleasing as that of the higher sphere.
He also saw for the next astronomy, which is the astronomy of Saturn, an immaterial self that was neither one of the animals he had seen before nor another, like the image of the sun that appears in a mirror reflected from a mirror opposite the sun, and he also saw for this self the same splendor and pleasure that he had seen for the previous one.
He still sees for each astronomy a separate self that is innocent of matter and is neither one of the previous selves nor another, like the image of the sun reflecting from mirror to mirror, arranged in order according to the order of the planets.
He saw for each of these selves such beauty, splendor, pleasure, and joy as no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no human heart has thought of, until he came to the world of the universe and corruption, which is all the stuffing of the moon's orbit, and saw a self that is free from matter and is neither one of the selves that he had seen before it, nor is it anything else.
This Self has seventy thousand faces with seventy thousand mouths, and in each face there are seventy thousand mouths, and in each mouth there are seventy thousand tongues that praise, sanctify, and glorify the One True Self without ceasing.
He saw for this self, which he imagined to be many and not many, the same perfection and pleasure as he had seen for the one before it.
It is as if this self is the image of the sun appearing in the swirling water, reflected from the last of the mirrors to which the reflection ended, in the order of the first mirror that met the sun itself.
Then he saw a different self, and if the seventy-thousand-faceted self could be a part of it, we would say that it was a part of it.
If it were not for the fact that this self happened after it wasn't there, we would say that it is her!
If it wasn't specific to his body when it happened, we would say that it didn't happen.
In this rank, he has seen selves like himself in objects that were and then ceased to exist and in objects that are still with him in existence, which are so numerous that they are infinitely numerous if they can be said to be many or all united if they can be said to be one.
He saw for himself and for those who are in his rank of beauty, splendor, and infinite pleasure what no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no human heart has thought of, nor can it be described by those who describe it, nor can it be comprehended except by those who are knowledgeable.
He saw many beings who were separated from matter as if they were rusty mirrors that had been corrupted by slag, yet they turned their faces away from the clear mirrors in which the image of the sun was projected.
He saw the ugliness and imperfection of these souls that he had never imagined, and saw them in endless pain and sorrow, surrounded by a marquee of torment, burned by the fire of the veil, and posted with saws between discomfort and attraction.
He looked closely at it and saw a great horror, a great calamity, an intense creation, eloquent judgments, leveling, blowing, creating, and copying.
His senses came back to him, and he awoke from his trance-like state, and his foot slipped from that position, and the sensible world appeared to him, and the divine world was absent from him; for the two could not meet in the same state.
If you say, "It appears from what you have narrated from this sighting that the separate selves, if they are of an ever-present body that does not corrupt, such as the planets, are ever-present, and if they are of a corruptible body, such as a talking animal, they are corrupted, decayed, and vanished, as exemplified in the mirrors of reflection, for the image is stable only by the stability of the mirror, and if the mirror is corrupted, the image is corrupted and decayed," I say to you. How quickly you forget the covenant and dissolve the link.
We did not present to you that the field of expression here is narrow and that words in any case create the illusion of something other than the truth, and that which you have created by making the example and the represented the same in all respects.
The sun, its light, its image, its shape, mirrors, and the images in them are all things that are inseparable from bodies and are only sustained by them and in them.
 Therefore, it is dependent on it for its existence and invalidated by its invalidity.
As for the divine selves and the divine spirits, they are all innocent of bodies and their appendages, and they are completely detached from them, so they have no connection or attachment to them.
In addition to them, bodies are null and void, whether they exist or exist or not, but their connection and attachment is to the One True Self, who is their beginning, beginning, cause, and creator, and who gives them permanence and extends them by survival and perpetuity.
If they could not exist, the bodies would not exist, as they are their beginnings, just as if the One True Self could not exist, all these selves would not exist, nor would the bodies, nor would the entire sensory world, and there would be no existence, as everything is connected to each other.
Although the tangible world is a shadow of the divine world, and the divine world is independent of it and innocent of it, it is nevertheless impossible to impose its non-existence, since it inevitably belongs to the divine world, but its corruption is to be altered and not to be eliminated altogether, and this is how the dear Book speaks wherever this meaning occurs from it in changing the mountains and making them like grass and people like brushes and the sun and moon and exploding the seas on the day when the earth is changed from the earth and the heavens.
This is as much as I have been able to tell you about what Hayy ibn Yaqzaan saw in that honorable place, so do not seek to add to it from the point of view of words, for this is impossible.
When he returned to the tangible world after his wanderings, he was tired of the costs of the worldly life and his longing for the ultimate life intensified, so he sought to return to that place in the way he had first sought it, until he reached it more easily than the first endeavor and lasted longer in it again than in the first.
Then he returned to the world of sense.
 Then he had to reach his shrine afterward, which was easier for him than the first two and lasted longer.
The access to that honorable place became easier and the permanence of it became longer and longer until he could reach it whenever he wished and could not leave it except when he wished, so that he stayed in that place and never departed from it except for the necessities of his body, which he had minimized until there was no less.
In all of this, he wants God to relieve him from all his body, which calls him to leave his position, so that he may always be free of his pleasure and free from the pain he feels when he turns away from his position to the necessity of the body.
